<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<subsection xml:id="ws-fraction-multiplication" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Fraction Multiplication</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
			This worksheet references topics from Sections 2.4 and 2.5.
		</p>
	</introduction>
	<worksheet xml:id="worksheet-fraction-multiplication">
		<title>Worksheet: Fraction Multiplication</title>
		<objectives>
			<ul>
				<li>Multiply fractions by whole numbers.</li>
				<li>Multiply fractions by other fractions.</li>
				<li>Divide fractions using reciprocals.</li>
				<li>Begin simplifying fractions.</li>
			</ul>
		</objectives>
		<page>
			<exercisegroup cols="3">
				<title>Multiplication with Whole Numbers and Fractions</title>
				<introduction>
					<p>
						Multiply each pair of numbers. Can you write the product as a whole number?
					</p>
				</introduction>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>2 \cdot \dfrac{3}{7}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>36 \cdot \dfrac{1}{4}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\dfrac{4}{5} \cdot 5</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
			</exercisegroup>
			<exercisegroup cols="2">
				<title>Visualization</title>
				<introduction>
					<p>The picture shows a rectangle with area <m>60 \text{in}^2</m> divided into thirds.</p> 
					<image width="80%">
						<latex-image>
							<![CDATA[
								\begin{tikzpicture}
								\filldraw[thick, color=red, fill=red!30] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (5, 4) -- (0,4);
								\filldraw[thick, color=red, fill=red!30] (5,0) -- (10,0) -- (10,4) -- (5,4); 
								\draw[thick, color=red] (10,0) -- (15,0) -- (15,4) -- (10,4); 
								\draw (7.5, -0.6) node {$15$ in};
								\draw (16,2) node {$4$ in};

								\end{tikzpicture}
							]]>
						</latex-image>
					</image>
				</introduction>
				<exercise workspace = "0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>What is the area of one third of the rectangle? Write this as a multiplication problem and evaluate.</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace = "0.25in">
					<statement>
					<p>What is the area of the shaded region of the rectangle? Write this as a multiplication problem and evaluate.</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
			</exercisegroup>
			<exercise workspace = "0.5in">
				<statement>
					<p>How would you determine <m>\dfrac{1}{4}</m> of the shaded region? Write this as a multiplication problem and evaluate.</p>
				</statement>
			</exercise>
		</page>
		<page>
			<exercisegroup cols="3">
				<title>Multiplication with Fractions and Fractions</title>
				<introduction>
					<p>
						Multiply each pair of fractions. Can you write the product as a whole number?
					</p>
				</introduction>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\dfrac{14}{9} \cdot \dfrac{1}{9}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\dfrac{14}{2} \cdot \dfrac{2}{7}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\dfrac{2}{3} \cdot \dfrac{3}{2}</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\left(\dfrac{1}{4}\right)^2</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\left(\dfrac{5}{6}\right)\left(\dfrac{3}{4}\right)</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<statement>
						<p>
							<m>\left(\dfrac{49}{42}\right)\left(\dfrac{12}{7}\right)</m>
						</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
			</exercisegroup>
			<exercise workspace="0.5in">
				<statement>
					<p>
							Write down the formula to calculate the area of a triangle. Describe what each <em>variable</em> in the formula stands for.
					</p>
				</statement>
			</exercise>
			<exercisegroup cols="2">
				<title>Triangle Areas</title>
				<introduction>
					<p>Use the formula for a triangle to calculate the areas of each triangle.</p>
				</introduction>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<introduction>
					<image width="60%">
						<latex-image>
							<![CDATA[
								\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (5,0) -- (2,4) -- (0,0);
								\draw[thick, dotted] (2,0) -- (2,4);
								\draw (3, 1) node {$12$ mm};
								\draw (2,-0.5) node {$15$ mm};
								\end{tikzpicture}
							]]>
						</latex-image>
					</image>
					</introduction>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<introduction>
					<image width="60%">
						<latex-image>
							<![CDATA[
								\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (4,2) -- (0,0);
								\draw[thick, dotted] (2,0) -- (4,0) -- (4,2);
								\draw (4.5, 1) node {$8$ in};
								\draw (1,-0.5) node {$8$ in};
								\end{tikzpicture}
							]]>
						</latex-image>
					</image>
					</introduction>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<introduction>
					<image width="60%">
						<latex-image>
							<![CDATA[
								\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (4,-2) -- (3,-2) -- (0,0);
								\draw[thick, dotted] (0,0) -- (0,-2) -- (3,-2);
								\draw (3.5, -2.5) node {$\dfrac{16}{9}$ yd};
								\draw (-1,-1) node {$3$ yd};
								\end{tikzpicture}
							]]>
						</latex-image>
					</image>
					</introduction>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="0.25in">
					<introduction>
					<image width="60%">
						<latex-image>
							<![CDATA[
								\begin{tikzpicture}
								\draw[thick] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (3,-1) -- (0,0);
								\draw[thick, dotted] (3,0) -- (3,-1);
								\draw (2,0.5) node {$5$ in};
								\draw (2.5,-0.5) node {$\frac{8}{5}$ in};
								\end{tikzpicture}
							]]>
						</latex-image>
					</image>
					</introduction>
				</exercise>
			</exercisegroup>
		</page>
		<page>
			<exercisegroup>
				<title>Word Problems</title>
				<exercise workspace="1in">
					<statement>
						<p>Tracy has half of a leftover pizza in the fridge. If he splits this up into 3 meals, how much of a pizza will each meal be? Write this as a multiplication problem and evaluate.</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
				<exercise workspace="1in">
					<statement>
						<p>Max is a woodworker and needs four <m>\frac{7}{8}</m>-yd boards for a project. How many yards of lumber does he need? Write this as a multiplication problem and evaluate, giving your answer as a mixed number.</p>
					</statement>
				</exercise>
			</exercisegroup>
			<exercise workspace = ".5in">
				<title>Self Reflection</title>
				<p>On a scale of 1-5, how confident are you with the material in this worksheet?</p>
				<p>Were any of the exercises confusing or frustrating? If so, identify them here and
					write down your plan to master those topics.</p>
			</exercise>
		</page>
	</worksheet>
</subsection>
